sident Population: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2017 (PEPANNRES): Minor Civil Divisions \u2013 New Hampshire|accessdate=November 14, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213183945/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/PEP/2017/PEPANNRES/0400000US33.06100|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 11,260 people, 3,119 households, and 1,797 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 220 people per square&nbsp;mile (86/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,278 housing units at an average density of 65.2 per square mile (25.2/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the town was 81.0% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.4% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]], 0.8% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 10.8% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.7% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 3.2% from two or more races.  [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were  3.9% of the population.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/SF1DP1/0600000US3300933860| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (DP-1), Hanover town, Grafton County, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213234516/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/SF1DP1/0600000US3300933860| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were 3,119 households out of which 27.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 42.4% were non-families. 31.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.95.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\"/>\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 27.8% at or under the age of 19, 25.5% from 20 to 24, 14.4% from 25 to 44, 18.6% from 45 to 64, and 13.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 23 years.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\"/>\n\nFor the period 2010-14, the estimated [[median income]] for a household in the town was $94,063, and the median income for a family was $129,000. Male full-time workers had a median income of $87,550 versus $53,141 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $34,140. About 2.0% of families and 12.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.4% of those under age 18 and 4.8% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/14_5YR/DP03/0600000US3300933860| title=Selected Economic Characteristics: 2010-2014 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates (DP03), Hanover town, Grafton County, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213132832/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/14_5YR/DP03/0600000US3300933860| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:1em 0 1em 1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Hanover town vote<br /> by party in presidential elections'''<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://sos.nh.gov/ElectResults.aspx |title = State Election Results - NHSOS}}</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n![[Republican Party (United States)|GOP]]\n![[Democratic Party (United States)|DEM]]\n!Others\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|11.94% ''926''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''84.63%''' ''6,561''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.43% ''266''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|23.67% ''1,727''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''74.97%''' ''5,469''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.36% ''99''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2008|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|17.67% ''1,328''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''81.69%''' ''6,140''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.64% ''48''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2004|2004]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|21.70% ''1,444''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.42%''' ''5,152''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.89% ''59''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2000|2000]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|29.56% ''1,541''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.05%''' ''3,391''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.39% ''281''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 1996|1996]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|31.71% ''1,424''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.16%''' ''2,836''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.12% ''230''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 1992|1992]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|25.91% ''1,201''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''62.70%''' ''2,906''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|11.39% ''528''\n|}\n\nIn the [[New Hampshire Senate]], Hanover is included in the 5th District and is represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Martha S. Hennessey. On the New Hampshire Executive Council, Hanover is in the 1st District and is represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Michael J. Cryans]]. In the United States House of Representatives, Hanover is a part of [[New Hampshire's 2nd congressional district]] and is currently represented by Democrat [[Ann McLane Kuster]].\n\nLike most other college towns, Hanover is a liberal bastion and a Democratic stronghold in presidential elections. No Republican presidential nominee has managed to receive over 32 percent of the vote in the town in the past two decades. Hanover backed [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]] with 85 percent of the vote in 2016, providing the former [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] and [[U.S. Senator]] from [[New York (state)|New York]] with her largest margin of victory in the state of New Hampshire, which she narrowly won by 2,736 votes statewide. Her margin of victory in Hanover was by over twice that amount, allowing attribution that her margin in Hanover was what ultimately allowed her to carry the Granite State. However, Hanover did not back Clinton in the 2008 Democratic primary (supporting [[Barack Obama]] with 58.15 percent of the vote to Clinton's 26.11 percent) nor did it support her in the 2016 Democratic primary when voters opted for [[U.S. Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]] from neighboring [[Vermont]] with 53.04 percent of the vote.\n\n\nHanover: Hospital (TV Series)\n\nPremiere: Sep 26, 1999\n\nFinale: Dec 12, 2000\n\n\nUPN\n\nSeason One: September 26, 1999 - April 16, 2000 25 Episodes\n\nSeason Two: September 12, 2000 - December 12, 2000 14 Episodes\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:A Front View of Dartmouth College (1793).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Students playing [[cricket (game)|cricket]] at Dartmouth College in 1793]]\n;Public schools\n* [[Hanover High School (New Hampshire)|Hanover High School]]\n* Frances C. Richmond Middle School\n* Bernice A. Ray Elementary School\n\n;Universities\n*[[Dartmouth College]]\n\n;Private schools\n*The [[Clark Preparatory School|Clark School]] was at one time located in Hanover but merged with [[Cardigan Mountain School]] in the nearby town of [[Canaan, New Hampshire|Canaan]] in 1953.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cardigan Mountain School: History, 1945-1995 |last=Hopkins |first=Robert C. |authorlink= |author2=Rearick, Richard R. |year=1995 |publisher=Sherwin Dodge |location=Littleton, NH |isbn= |pages=81\u201388}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nHypertherm,<ref>[https://www.hypertherm.com/en-US/our-company/ Hypertherm]</ref> [[White Mountains Insurance Group]], and [[Daat Research Corp.]] are based in Hanover.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n;Water\nThe Hanover Water Company supplies water for downtown Hanover from several local reservoirs. The company is owned by Dartmouth College (52.8%) and the Town of Hanover (47.2%), with management by the Town of Hanover under a contract. In 2000, all full-time company employees became town employees. In recent years, the town has spent over $20&nbsp;million to upgrade main water lines, and will undergo another $6&nbsp;million project to build a new water treatment plant. Outside the downtown area, residents rely on private wells that are not maintained by the town.\n\n;Other utilities\n[[FairPoint Communications]] furnishes telephone communication. The municipality provides sewage treatment.\n\n==Plaudits==\n[[CNN]] and [[Money (magazine)|''Money'']] magazine rated Hanover the sixth best place to live in America in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2011/snapshots/PL3333780.html |title=Best Places to Live: Top 100 - Hanover, N.H. (6) |work=Money Magazine |publisher=Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company |accessdate=2011-11-01}}</ref> and the second best in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2007/moneymag/0707/gallery.BPTL_top_100.moneymag/2.html |title=Best Places to Live: Top 100 - Hanover, N.H. (2) |work=Money Magazine |publisher=Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company |accessdate=2011-02-08 }}</ref> \"This just might be the best college town,\" read the headline of a story in the January\u2013February 2017 issue of ''[[Yankee (magazine)|Yankee]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newengland.com/yankee-magazine/travel/new-hampshire/hanover-new-hampshire/|title=Hanover, New Hampshire {{!}} Could You Live Here? - New England Today|date=2016-12-17|newspaper=New England Today|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main list|List of people from Hanover, New Hampshire}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Hanover (New Hampshire)|Hanover, New Hampshire}}\n* [http://www.hanovernh.org Town website]\n* [http://www.hanoverchamber.org/ Hanover Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://www.thehowe.org/ Howe Library]\n* [http://www.nhes.nh.gov/elmi/products/cp/profiles-htm/hanover.htm New Hampshire Economic and Labor Market Information Bureau Profile]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = Hanover\n | North     = [[Thetford, Vermont]]\n | Northeast = [[Lyme, New Hampshire|Lyme]]\n | East      = [[Canaan, New Hampshire|Canaan]]\n | Southeast = [[Enfield, New Hampshire|Enfield]]\n | South     = [[Lebanon, New Hampshire|Lebanon]]\n | Southwest = [[Hartford, Vermont]]\n | West      = [[Norwich, Vermont]]\n | Northwest = [[Norwich, Vermont]]\n}}\n\n{{Grafton County, New Hampshire}}\n{{Connecticut River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hanover, New Hampshire| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1761]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Connecticut River]]\n[[Category:Towns in Grafton County, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Town in New Hampshire, United States}}\n{{lead rewrite|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Hanover, New Hampshire\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n|image_skyline            = HanoverNHMainStreet.jpg\n|image_seal               =\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Hanover Main Street\n|image_flag               =\n|image_map                = Grafton-Hanover-NH.png\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Grafton County, New Hampshire]]\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[New Hampshire]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Hampshire|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Grafton County, New Hampshire|Grafton]]\n|parts_type               = Villages\n|parts                    = [[Hanover (CDP), New Hampshire|Hanover]]<br>[[Etna, New Hampshire|Etna]]<br>Hanover&nbsp;Center\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             = [[Board of Selectmen]]\n|leader_name              = Peter L. Christie, Chair<br>Athos J. Rassias<br>William V. Geraghty<br>Nancy A. Carter<br>Joanna Whitcomb\n|leader_title1            = Town Manager\n|leader_name1             = Julia N. Griffin\n|established_title        = [[Incorporation (municipal government)|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = 1761\n|area_magnitude           = 1 E8\n|area_total_km2           = 130.2\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_km2            = 127.0\n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_km2           = 3.3\n|area_water_sq_mi         = \n|area_water_percent       = 2.52\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_note          =\n|population_total         = 11260\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset               = &minus;5\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time Zone|Eastern]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = &minus;4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|42|08|N|72|17|22|W|type:landmark_region:US-NH|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = 161\n|elevation_ft             = 528\n|website                  = {{URL|www.hanovernh.org}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = 03755 (Hanover)<br>03750 ([[Etna, New Hampshire|Etna]])\n|area_code                = [[Area code 603|603]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 33-33860\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0873619\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Hanover''' is a [[New England town|town]] along the [[Connecticut River]] in [[Grafton County, New Hampshire|Grafton County]], [[New Hampshire]], United States. The population was 11,260 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US3300933860| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Hanover town, Grafton County, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213130204/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0600000US3300933860| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Dartmouth College]] and the [[US Army Corps of Engineers]] [[Cold Regions Research and Engineering Laboratory]] are located in Hanover. The [[Appalachian Trail]] crosses the town.\n\nThe main village of the town, where 8,636 people resided at the 2010 census,<ref name=\"Census 2010 CDP\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US3333780| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Hanover CDP, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213043212/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US3333780| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> is defined as the [[Hanover (CDP), New Hampshire|Hanover census-designated place]] (CDP), and is located at the junctions of New Hampshire routes [[New Hampshire Route 10|10]], [[New Hampshire Route 10A|10A]], and [[New Hampshire Route 120|120]]. The town also contains the villages of [[Etna, New Hampshire|Etna]] and Hanover Center.\n\n==History==\nHanover was chartered by Governor [[Benning Wentworth]] on July 4, 1761, and in 1765\u20131766 its first European inhabitants arrived, the majority from [[Connecticut]]. Although the surface is uneven, the town developed into an agricultural community. Dartmouth College was established in 1769 beside the [[common land|Common]] at a village called \"the Plain\"\u2014an extensive and level tract of land a mile (1.6 kilometers) from the [[Connecticut River]], and about {{convert|150|ft}} above it.<ref name=Coolidge>{{Cite book | last = Coolidge | first = Austin J.|author2=John B. Mansfield | title = A History and Description of New England| publisher = A.J. Coolidge | year = 1859| location = Boston, Massachusetts| pages = [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_OcoMAAAAYAAJ/page/n556 516]\u2013519| url = https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_OcoMAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\nAt one point in its history, the southwest corner of Hanover was known as \"Dresden\", which in the 1780s joined other disgruntled New Hampshire towns along the Connecticut River that briefly defected to what was then the independent [[Vermont Republic]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The College on the Hill: A Dartmouth Chronicle |last=Hill |first=Ralph Nading |publisher=Dartmouth Publishing |year=1965 |isbn= |location=Hanover, NH |page=46 |quote= |doi = 10.1349/ddlp.1484}}</ref> After various political posturings, however, the towns returned to New Hampshire at the heated insistence of [[George Washington]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flowofhistory.org/themes/american_republic/western.php |title=The American Republic: 1760\u20131780: The Western Rebellion |work=New Hampshire Profile |first=Jere |last=Daniell |year=1976 |publisher=The Flow of History |accessdate=2011-02-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122132910/http://www.flowofhistory.org/themes/american_republic/western.php |archive-date=2010-11-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> One remnant of this era is that the name \"Dresden\" is still used in the [[Dresden School District]], an [[Hanover High School (New Hampshire)|interstate school district]] serving both Hanover and [[Norwich, Vermont]]\u2014the first and one of the few interstate school districts in the nation.\n\nThe film ''[[Winter Carnival (film)|Winter Carnival]]'' (1939) was shot in Hanover.<ref>Barth, Jack (1991). ''Roadside Hollywood: The Movie Lover's State-By-State Guide to Film Locations, Celebrity Hangouts, Celluloid Tourist Attractions, and More''. Contemporary Books. Page 249. {{ISBN|9780809243266}}.</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\n\"Hannover\" (as it was spelled in the 1761 charter and in its German original form as well) was named either after a local parish in [[Sprague, Connecticut]], or after the German [[House of Hanover]] in honor of the reigning British-Hanoverian king, [[George III]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hanovernh.org/about |title=About the Town of Hanover |publisher=www.hanovernh.org |accessdate=2011-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528152115/http://www.hanovernh.org/about |archivedate=2010-05-28 }}</ref> \nOriginally [[Hannover|Han(n)over]] is a city (capital) in [[Lower Saxony]], North [[Germany]]. The name of the German city derives from the [[Low German]] form of what is \"hohes Ufer\" in German, which translates into \"high shore\" in English, and describes the high shore of the [[Leine]] river. (see [[:de:Am Hohen Ufer]]; in German).\n\nWhile it is likely that the name \"Dresden\" derived from [[Dresden]] in Germany, it has also been suggested that it could derive directly from the old [[Sorbian languages|Sorbian]] word ''drezg'' (\"forest\") or ''Drezd'ane'', for an inhabitant of a forest.<ref>The settlers in the riverside forest, an appellation fully compatible with that of the early inhabitants of the Hanover Plain.</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~library/Library_Bulletin/Nov1997/HoefnagelClose.html| title=Dresden: What Is in the Name| author=Dick Hoefnagel and Virginia L. Close| accessdate=October 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|50.3|sqmi|1}}, of which {{convert|49.0|sqmi|1}} is land and {{convert|1.3|sqmi|1}} is water, comprising 2.52% of the town.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/> The primary settlement in Hanover, where over 75% of the town's population resides, is defined as the Hanover [[census-designated place]] (CDP) and contains the areas around Dartmouth College and the intersections of New Hampshire Routes [[New Hampshire Route 10|10]], [[New Hampshire Route 10A|10A]], and [[New Hampshire Route 120|120]]. The CDP has a total area of {{convert|5.0|sqmi|km2}}, of which {{convert|4.6|sqmi|km2}} is land and {{convert|0.4|sqmi|km2}} is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010 CDP\"/>\n\nHanover borders the towns of [[Lyme, New Hampshire|Lyme]], [[Canaan, New Hampshire|Canaan]], and [[Enfield, New Hampshire]]; [[Norwich, Vermont]]; and the city of [[Lebanon, New Hampshire]]. Inside the limits of Hanover are the small rural villages of [[Etna, New Hampshire|Etna]] and Hanover Center.\n\nThe highest point in Hanover is the north peak of [[Moose Mountain (New Hampshire)|Moose Mountain]], at {{convert|2313|ft|m}} above [[sea level]]. Hanover lies fully within the [[Connecticut River]] [[Drainage basin|watershed]].<ref name=watershed>{{cite book |title=Water Use in New Hampshire: An Activities Guide for Teachers |url=http://nh.water.usgs.gov/Publications/nh.intro.html |last=Foster |first=Debra H. |author2=Batorfalvy, Tatianna N. |author3= Medalie, Laura  |publisher=U.S. Department of the Interior and U.S. Geological Survey |year=1995}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of trails and nature preserves in Hanover, and the majority of these trails are suitable for [[snowshoe]]s and [[cross-country ski]]s. The Velvet Rocks Trail, located on the [[Appalachian Trail by state|Appalachian Trail]], has a number of [[rock climbing]] and [[bouldering]] spots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainproject.com/area/107529408/black-velvet-canyon-boulders|title=Climbing in Black Velvet Canyon Boulders, Red Rock|website=Mountain Project|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nHanover experiences a [[humid continental climate|warm summer continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Dfb''), with long, cold, snowy winters, and warm, humid summers. Temperatures average {{convert|19.0|\u00b0F|1}} in January to {{convert|70.9|\u00b0F|1}} in July, and the annual mean is {{convert|46.0|\u00b0F|1}}. Extremes range from {{convert|\u221240|\u00b0F}}, recorded on February 16, 1943,<ref name=\"Feb Averages\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/daily/03755?climoMonth=2|title=February Daily Averages for Hanover, NH (03755)|publisher=The Weather Channel|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> to 103&nbsp;\u00b0F (39&nbsp;\u00b0C), recorded on August 2, 1975.<ref name=\"Aug Averages\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/daily/03755?climoMonth=8|title=August Daily Averages for Hanover, NH (03755)|publisher=The Weather Channel|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Hanover, New Hampshire\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  64\n|Feb record high F =  63\n|Mar record high F =  86\n|Apr record high F =  93\n|May record high F =  96\n|Jun record high F =  98\n|Jul record high F = 101\n|Aug record high F = 103\n|Sep record high F =  97\n|Oct record high F =  87\n|Nov record high F =  79\n|Dec record high F =  70\n|year record high F =103\n|Jan high F = 29.3\n|Feb high F = 34.0\n|Mar high F = 43.5\n|Apr high F = 56.6\n|May high F = 70.4\n|Jun high F = 78.5\n|Jul high F = 82.9\n|Aug high F = 80.8\n|Sep high F = 71.3\n|Oct high F = 58.5\n|Nov high F = 45.6\n|Dec high F = 33.6\n|Jan low F =  8.7\n|Feb low F = 11.6\n|Mar low F = 22.1\n|Apr low F = 32.8\n|May low F = 44.1\n|Jun low F = 53.5\n|Jul low F = 58.8\n|Aug low F = 57.3\n|Sep low F = 49.4\n|Oct low F = 37.3\n|Nov low F = 28.4\n|Dec low F = 15.6\n|Jan record low F = -28\n|Feb record low F = -40\n|Mar record low F = -22\n|Apr record low F =   7\n|May record low F =  22\n|Jun record low F =  30\n|Jul record low F =  39\n|Aug record low F =  33\n|Sep record low F =  22\n|Oct record low F =  13\n|Nov record low F = -12\n|Dec record low F = -34\n|year record low F= -40\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.97\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.34\n|Mar precipitation inch = 2.87\n|Apr precipitation inch = 3.02\n|May precipitation inch = 3.45\n|Jun precipitation inch = 3.36\n|Jul precipitation inch = 3.69\n|Aug precipitation inch = 3.70\n|Sep precipitation inch = 3.54\n|Oct precipitation inch = 3.47\n|Nov precipit