085\n|1880= 2147\n|1890= 1817\n|1900= 1884\n|1910= 2075\n|1920= 2264\n|1930= 3043\n|1940= 3425\n|1950= 6259\n|1960= 7329\n|1970= 8494\n|1980= 9119\n|1990= 9212\n|2000= 10850\n|2010= 11260\n|estyear=2017\n|estimate=11485\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2017\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/PEP/2017/PEPANNRES/0400000US33.06100|title=Annual Estimates of the Resident Population: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2017 (PEPANNRES): Minor Civil Divisions \u2013 New Hampshire|accessdate=November 14, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213183945/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/PEP/2017/PEPANNRES/0400000US33.06100|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 11,260 people, 3,119 households, and 1,797 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 220 people per square&nbsp;mile (86/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,278 housing units at an average density of 65.2 per square mile (25.2/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the town was 81.0% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.4% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]], 0.8% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 10.8% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.7% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 3.2% from two or more races.  [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were  3.9% of the population.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/SF1DP1/0600000US3300933860| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (DP-1), Hanover town, Grafton County, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213234516/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/SF1DP1/0600000US3300933860| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were 3,119 households out of which 27.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 4.7% had a female householder with no husband present, and 42.4% were non-families. 31.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.95.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\"/>\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 27.8% at or under the age of 19, 25.5% from 20 to 24, 14.4% from 25 to 44, 18.6% from 45 to 64, and 13.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 23 years.<ref name=\"Census 2010 DP-1\"/>\n\nFor the period 2010-14, the estimated [[median income]] for a household in the town was $94,063, and the median income for a family was $129,000. Male full-time workers had a median income of $87,550 versus $53,141 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $34,140. About 2.0% of families and 12.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.4% of those under age 18 and 4.8% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/14_5YR/DP03/0600000US3300933860| title=Selected Economic Characteristics: 2010-2014 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates (DP03), Hanover town, Grafton County, New Hampshire| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=June 22, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213132832/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/14_5YR/DP03/0600000US3300933860| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:1em 0 1em 1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Hanover town vote<br /> by party in presidential elections'''<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://sos.nh.gov/ElectResults.aspx |title = State Election Results - NHSOS}}</ref>\n|-\n! Year\n![[Republican Party (United States)|GOP]]\n![[Democratic Party (United States)|DEM]]\n!Others\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|11.94% ''926''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''84.63%''' ''6,561''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.43% ''266''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|23.67% ''1,727''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''74.97%''' ''5,469''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.36% ''99''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2008|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|17.67% ''1,328''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''81.69%''' ''6,140''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.64% ''48''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2004|2004]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|21.70% ''1,444''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.42%''' ''5,152''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.89% ''59''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 2000|2000]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|29.56% ''1,541''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.05%''' ''3,391''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.39% ''281''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 1996|1996]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|31.71% ''1,424''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.16%''' ''2,836''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.12% ''230''\n|-  \n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in New Hampshire, 1992|1992]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Republican}}|25.91% ''1,201''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''62.70%''' ''2,906''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|11.39% ''528''\n|}\n\nIn the [[New Hampshire Senate]], Hanover is included in the 5th District and is represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Martha S. Hennessey. On the New Hampshire Executive Council, Hanover is in the 1st District and is represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Michael J. Cryans]]. In the United States House of Representatives, Hanover is a part of [[New Hampshire's 2nd congressional district]] and is currently represented by Democrat [[Ann McLane Kuster]].\n\nLike most other college towns, Hanover is a liberal bastion and a Democratic stronghold in presidential elections. No Republican presidential nominee has managed to receive over 32 percent of the vote in the town in the past two decades. Hanover backed [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]] with 85 percent of the vote in 2016, providing the former [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] and [[U.S. Senator]] from [[New York (state)|New York]] with her largest margin of victory in the state of New Hampshire, which she narrowly won by 2,736 votes statewide. Her margin of victory in Hanover was by over twice that amount, allowing attribution that her margin in Hanover was what ultimately allowed her to carry the Granite State. However, Hanover did not back Clinton in the 2008 Democratic primary (supporting [[Barack Obama]] with 58.15 percent of the vote to Clinton's 26.11 percent) nor did it support her in the 2016 Democratic primary when voters opted for [[U.S. Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]] from neighboring [[Vermont]] with 53.04 percent of the vote.\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:A Front View of Dartmouth College (1793).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Students playing [[cricket (game)|cricket]] at Dartmouth College in 1793]]\n;Public schools\n* [[Hanover High School (New Hampshire)|Hanover High School]]\n* Frances C. Richmond Middle School\n* Bernice A. Ray Elementary School\n\n;Universities\n*[[Dartmouth College]]\n\n;Private schools\n*The [[Clark Preparatory School|Clark School]] was at one time located in Hanover but merged with [[Cardigan Mountain School]] in the nearby town of [[Canaan, New Hampshire|Canaan]] in 1953.<ref>{{cite book |title=Cardigan Mountain School: History, 1945-1995 |last=Hopkins |first=Robert C. |authorlink= |author2=Rearick, Richard R. |year=1995 |publisher=Sherwin Dodge |location=Littleton, NH |isbn= |pages=81\u201388}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nHypertherm,<ref>[https://www.hypertherm.com/en-US/our-company/ Hypertherm]</ref> [[White Mountains Insurance Group]], and [[Daat Research Corp.]] are based in Hanover.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n;Water\nThe Hanover Water Company supplies water for downtown Hanover from several local reservoirs. The company is owned by Dartmouth College (52.8%) and the Town of Hanover (47.2%), with management by the Town of Hanover under a contract. In 2000, all full-time company employees became town employees. In recent years, the town has spent over $20&nbsp;million to upgrade main water lines, and will undergo another $6&nbsp;million project to build a new water treatment plant. Outside the downtown area, residents rely on private wells that are not maintained by the town.\n\n;Other utilities\n[[FairPoint Communications]] furnishes telephone communication. The municipality provides sewage treatment.\n\n==Plaudits==\n[[CNN]] and [[Money (magazine)|''Money'']] magazine rated Hanover the sixth best place to live in America in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2011/snapshots/PL3333780.html |title=Best Places to Live: Top 100 - Hanover, N.H. (6) |work=Money Magazine |publisher=Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company |accessdate=2011-11-01}}</ref> and the second best in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2007/moneymag/0707/gallery.BPTL_top_100.moneymag/2.html |title=Best Places to Live: Top 100 - Hanover, N.H. (2) |work=Money Magazine |publisher=Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company |accessdate=2011-02-08 }}</ref> \"This just might be the best college town,\" read the headline of a story in the January\u2013February 2017 issue of ''[[Yankee (magazine)|Yankee]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newengland.com/yankee-magazine/travel/new-hampshire/hanover-new-hampshire/|title=Hanover, New Hampshire {{!}} Could You Live Here? - New England Today|date=2016-12-17|newspaper=New England Today|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main list|List of people from Hanover, New Hampshire}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Hanover (New Hampshire)|Hanover, New Hampshire}}\n* [http://www.hanovernh.org Town website]\n* [http://www.hanoverchamber.org/ Hanover Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://www.thehowe.org/ Howe Library]\n* [http://www.nhes.nh.gov/elmi/products/cp/profiles-htm/hanover.htm New Hampshire Economic and Labor Market Information Bureau Profile]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = Hanover\n | North     = [[Thetford, Vermont]]\n | Northeast = [[Lyme, New Hampshire|Lyme]]\n | East      = [[Canaan, New Hampshire|Canaan]]\n | Southeast = [[Enfield, New Hampshire|Enfield]]\n | South     = [[Lebanon, New Hampshire|Lebanon]]\n | Southwest = [[Hartford, Vermont]]\n | West      = [[Norwich, Vermont]]\n | Northwest = [[Norwich, Vermont]]\n}}\n\n{{Grafton County, New Hampshire}}\n{{Connecticut River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hanover, New Hampshire| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1761]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Connecticut River]]\n[[Category:Towns in Grafton County, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kaseyk2019", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Laugh)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanover,_New_Hampshire"}
{"title_page": "Sachrang Formation", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Sachrang Formation\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian|Lower-Middle Toarcian]]<br>~{{fossilrange|180}}<ref name=Named/>\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = Black Shales, Limestone & Marl<ref name=Named/>\n| otherlithology = Lithified limestone\n| namedfor       = [[Sachrang (Austria)|Sachrang]], a location in northern Austria\n| namedby        =Jacobshagen <ref name=Named>Jacobshagen, V. (1965). Die Allg\u00e4u-Schichten (Jura-Fleckenmergel) zwischen\nWettersteingebirge und Rhein. Wien: Geol. Bundesanstalt</ref>\n| year_ts        = 1965<ref name=Named/>\n| region         = [[Bavaric Nappe]]-Northern Tirol\n| country        = *{{Flag|Austria}}\n| coordinates    =  \n| unitof         = [[Allg\u00e4u Formation]]\n| subunits       = *B\u00e4chental section\n*Sachrang Member\n*Unken Member\n| underlies      = [[Klaus Formation]]\n| overlies       = \n| thickness      = {{convert|15|-|27|m|ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=Named/>\n| extent         = \n| area           =\n| map            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Sachrang Formation'''  is a [[geological formation]] in [[Austria]], dating to 180 [[mya (unit)|million years ago]], and covering the lower and middle [[Toarcian]] stage of the [[Jurassic]] Period. It is among the most important formations of the Toarcian Boundary on the Carpathian realm, being the regional equivalent of the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=Named/> The Sachrang Formation is included inside the major stratigaphic groups found on the Tirol Mountains on center Europe, where is equivalent to the  Saubach Member of the [[Adnet Formation]], also from the Toarcian stage.<ref name=Ebli>Ebli, O., Vet\u0151, I., Lobitzer, H., Sajg\u00f3, C., Dem\u00e9ny, A., & Het\u00e9nyi, M. (1998). Primary productivity and early diagenesis in the Toarcian Tethys on the example of the Mn-rich black shales of the Sachrang Formation, Northern Calcareous Alps. Organic Geochemistry, 29(5-7), 1635-1647.</ref> It is part of the series of formations with the presence of Toarcian black shales, being among the most important of the Alpine-Mediterranean domain.<ref name=Ebli/>\n\n==Geology==\nThe Jurassic Sedimentation is subdivided on several different units, with drastic changes in the [[Northern Calcareous Alps]]. At the Toarcian stage [[Carbonate Platform]]s collapsed and several types of bottom reliefs where generated due to tectonic activity, where on  the submarine swells the red nodular [[Limestone]]s with a exprossure of 20 m of the [[Adnet Formation]] where deposited on zones of basinal sedimentology, know due to the presence of grey limestone and marl on a up to 200 m layer of the [[Allgau Formation]].<ref name=Ebli/> The Marls of the Sachrang Formation are part of the Lower Toarcian \"Black Shale deposition\", contemporaneous of other events on central Germany and England.<ref name=Ebli/> The Sachrang Formation was geologically divided in the Sachrang Member, that presents typical development of a basinal area and the Unken Member, with benthic microfossils with suboxic water influence.<ref name=Ebli/>\n\n\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Italy]]\n* [[Toarcian turnover]]\n* [[:Category:Toarcian Stage|Toarcian formations]]\n**[[Marne di Monte Serrone]], Italy\n** [[Calcare di Sogno]], Italy\n** [[Posidonia Shale]], [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] in Germany\n** [[Ciechocinek Formation]], Germany and Poland\n** [[Krempachy Marl Formation]], Poland and Slovakia\n** [[Lava Formation]], Lithuania\n** [[Azilal Group]], North Africa\n** [[Whitby Mudstone]], England\n** [[Fernie Formation]], Alberta and British Columbia\n*** [[Poker Chip Shale]]\n** [[Whiteaves Formation]], British Columbia\n** [[Navajo Sandstone]], Utah\n** [[Los Molles Formation]], Argentina\n** [[Mawson Formation]], Antarctica\n** [[Kandreho Formation]], Madagascar\n** [[Kota Formation]], India\n** [[Cattamarra Coal Measures]], Australia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jurassic System of Europe]]\n[[Category:Toarcian Stage]]\n[[Category:Marl formations]]\n[[Category:Open marine deposits]]\n[[Category:Fossiliferous stratigraphic units of Europe]]\n[[Category:Marche|Formations]]\n[[Category:Geology of Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Sachrang Formation\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian|Lower-Middle Toarcian]]<br>~{{fossilrange|180}}<ref name=Named/>\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = Black Shales, Limestone & Marl<ref name=Named/>\n| otherlithology = Lithified limestone\n| namedfor       = [[Sachrang (Austria)|Sachrang]], a location in northern Austria\n| namedby        =Jacobshagen <ref name=Named>Jacobshagen, V. (1965). Die Allg\u00e4u-Schichten (Jura-Fleckenmergel) zwischen\nWettersteingebirge und Rhein. Wien: Geol. Bundesanstalt</ref>\n| year_ts        = 1965<ref name=Named/>\n| region         = [[Bavaric Nappe]]-Northern Tirol\n| country        = *{{Flag|Austria}}\n| coordinates    =  \n| unitof         = [[Allg\u00e4u Formation]]\n| subunits       = \n| underlies      = [[Klaus Formation]]\n| overlies       = \n| thickness      = {{convert|15|-|20|m|ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=Named/>\n| extent         = \n| area           =\n| map            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Sachrang Formation'''  is a [[geological formation]] in [[Austria]], dating to 180 [[mya (unit)|million years ago]], and covering the lower and middle [[Toarcian]] stage of the [[Jurassic]] Period. It is among the most important formations of the Toarcian Boundary on the Carpathian realm, being the regional equivalent of the [[Posidonia Shale]].<ref name=Named/> The Sachrang Formation is included inside the major stratigaphic groups <ref name=quimic1>Suan, G., Schl\u00f6gl, J., & Mattioli, E. (2016). Bio- and chemostratigraphy of the Toarcian organic-rich deposits of some key successions of the Alpine Tethys. Newsletters on Stratigraphy, 49(3), 401\u2013419. doi:10.1127/nos/2016/0078 </ref>\n<ref name=IronA>Reinhardt, M., Duda, J. P., Blumenberg, M., Ostertag\u2010Henning, C., Reitner, J., Heim, C., & Thiel, V. (2018). The taphonomic fate of isorenieratene in Lower Jurassic shales\u2014controlled by iron?. Geobiology, 16(3), 237-251.</ref><ref name=Ebli>Ebli, O., Vet\u0151, I., Lobitzer, H., Sajg\u00f3, C., Dem\u00e9ny, A., & Het\u00e9nyi, M. (1998). Primary productivity and early diagenesis in the Toarcian Tethys on the example of the Mn-rich black shales of the Sachrang Formation, Northern Calcareous Alps. Organic Geochemistry, 29(5-7), 1635-1647.</ref> \n\n==Geology==\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Italy]]\n* [[Toarcian turnover]]\n* [[:Category:Toarcian Stage|Toarcian formations]]\n**[[Marne di Monte Serrone]], Italy\n** [[Calcare di Sogno]], Italy\n** [[Posidonia Shale]], [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] in Germany\n** [[Ciechocinek Formation]], Germany and Poland\n** [[Krempachy Marl Formation]], Poland and Slovakia\n** [[Lava Formation]], Lithuania\n** [[Azilal Group]], North Africa\n** [[Whitby Mudstone]], England\n** [[Fernie Formation]], Alberta and British Columbia\n*** [[Poker Chip Shale]]\n** [[Whiteaves Formation]], British Columbia\n** [[Navajo Sandstone]], Utah\n** [[Los Molles Formation]], Argentina\n** [[Mawson Formation]], Antarctica\n** [[Kandreho Formation]], Madagascar\n** [[Kota Formation]], India\n** [[Cattamarra Coal Measures]], Australia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jurassic System of Europe]]\n[[Category:Toarcian Stage]]\n[[Category:Marl formations]]\n[[Category:Open marine deposits]]\n[[Category:Fossiliferous stratigraphic units of Europe]]\n[[Category:Marche|Formations]]\n[[Category:Geology of Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Yewtharaptor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sachrang_Formation"}
{"title_page": "Dinner", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Dinner time|other uses|Dinner Time (disambiguation){{!}}Dinner Time}}\n{{Meals}}\n'''Dinner''' usually refers to what is in many Western cultures the largest and most formal [[meal]] of the day, which many Westerners eat in the [[evening]].  Historically the largest meal used to be eaten around [[noon|midday]], and called dinner.<ref name=oed>{{cite OED|dinner}}</ref>  In Western cultures, especially among the elite, it gradually migrated later in the day over the 16th to 19th centuries.<ref name=\"mcm\">{{cite web|author1=McMillan S|title=What Time is Dinner?|url=http://www.history-magazine.com/dinner2.html|publisher=History Magazine|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=2001}}</ref>  However, the word \"dinner\" can have different meanings depending on culture, and may mean a meal of any size eaten at any time of day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olver|first=Lynne|title=Meal times|url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodfaq7.html#mealtimes|publisher=Lynne Olver|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>  In particular it is still sometimes used for a meal at noon or in the early afternoon on special occasions, such as a [[Christmas dinner]].<ref name=mcm/>  In very hot climates people have always tended to eat the main meal in the evening, after the temperature has fallen.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Family eating meal.jpg|thumb|Dinner with family]]\nThe word is from the Old French ({{circa|1300}}) ''disner'', meaning \"dine\", from the stem of Gallo-Romance ''desjunare'' (\"to break one's fast\"), from Latin ''dis-'' (which indicates the opposite of an action) + Late Latin ''ieiunare'' (\"to fast\"), from Latin ''ieiunus'' (\"fasting, hungry\").<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=dinner Etymology of \"dinner\"] from Online Dictionary. Accessed November 11, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=dine Etymology of \"dine\"] from Online Dictionary. Accessed November 11, 2009.</ref> The [[Romanian language|Romanian]] word ''dejun'' and the [[French language|French]] ''d\u00e9jeuner'' retain this etymology and to some extent the meaning (whereas the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word ''desayuno'' and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''desjejum'' are related but are exclusively used for breakfast). Eventually, the term shifted to referring to the heavy main meal of the day, even if it had been preceded by a breakfast meal (or even both breakfast and lunch).\n\n==Time of day==\n===Historical===\nReflecting the typical custom of the 17th century, [[Louis XIV]] dined at noon, with a [[supper]] at 10pm.<ref>Strong, 250</ref>   But in [[Europe]], dinner began to move later in the day during the 1700s, due to developments in work practices, lighting, financial status, and cultural changes.<ref name=mcm/>  The fashionable hour for dinner continued to be incrementally postponed during the 18th century, to two and three in the afternoon, and in 1765 King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] dined at 4pm, though his infant sons had theirs with their governess at 2pm, leaving time to visit the queen as she dressed for dinner with the king.<ref>\"Text adapted from ''The Conversation Piece: Scenes of fashionable life'', London, 2009\", at  [http://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/search#/1/collection/400146/queen-charlotte-1744-1818-with-her-two-eldest-sons \"Johan Joseph Zoffany (Frankfurt 1733-London 1810), Queen Charlotte (1744\u20131818) with her Two Eldest Sons  c.1765\"] on the Royal Collection website.</ref>  But in France [[Marie Antoinette]], when still [[Dauphine of France]] in 1770, wrote that when at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Choisy]] the court still dined at 2pm, with a supper after the theatre at around 10pm, before bed at 1 or 1.30am.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=A7E-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA110 quoted in] ''The Origins of Contemporary France: The ancient r\u00e9gime'', by [[Hippolyte Taine]], Bk2, ch.1, p. 110 in this edition</ref>\n\nAt the time of the [[First French Empire]] an English traveler to [[Paris]] remarked upon the \"abominable habit of dining as late as seven in the evening\".<ref>Quote in Ian Kelly, ''Cooking for Kings: the life of Antonin Car\u00eame the first celebrity chef'', 2003:78. For guests of [[Talleyrand]] at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Valen\u00e7ay]], dinner under [[Antonin Car\u00eame|Car\u00eame]] was even later.</ref>  By about 1850 English middle-class dinners were around 5 or 6pm, allowing men to arrive back from work, but there was a continuing pressure for the hour to drift later, led by the elite who did not have to work set hours, and as commutes got longer as cities expanded.  In the mid-19th century the issue was something of a social minefield, with a generational element.  [[John Ruskin]], once he married in 1848, dined at 6pm, which his parents thought \"unhealthy\".  [[Mrs Gaskell]] dined between 4 and 5pm.  The fictional [[The Diary of a Nobody|Mr Pooter]], a lower middle-class Londoner in 1888-89 and a diner at 5pm, was invited by his son to dine at 8pm, but \"I said we did not pretend to be fashionable people, and would like the dinner earlier\".<ref>Flanders, 229-230</ref>\n\nThe satirical novel ''Living for Appearances'' (1855) by [[Henry Mayhew]] and his brother [[Augustus Mayhew|Augustus]] begins with the views of the hero on the matter.  He dines at 7pm, and often complains of \"the disgusting and tradesman-like custom of early dining\", say at 2pm.  The \"Royal hour\" he regards as 8pm, but he does not aspire to that.  He tells people \"Tell me when you dine, and I will tell you what you are\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aq4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1 ''Living for Appearances''] (1855), p. 1, by [[Henry Mayhew]] and his brother [[Augustus Mayhew|Augustus]]; Flanders, 230</ref>\n\n===Modern===\n[[File:Filet de b\u0153uf.jpg|thumb|A [[filet mignon]] dinner with mashed potato, string beans and mushrooms.]]\nIn many modern usages, the term ''dinner'' refers to the evening meal, which is now typically the largest meal of the day in Western cultures. When this meaning is used, the preceding meals are usually referred to as [[breakfast]], [[lunch]] and perhaps a [[Tea (meal)|tea]].<ref name=mcm/><ref name=\"perry\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/aug/03/tea-with-grayson-perry-supper-dinner |title=Tea with Grayson Perry. Or is it dinner, or supper? |newspaper=The Guardian |date=August 2012 |accessdate=2013-08-15 |location=London}}</ref>  [[Supper]] is now often an alternative term for dinner; originally this was always a later secondary evening meal, after an early dinner.\n\nThe divide between different meanings of \"dinner\" is not cut-and-dried based on either geography or socioeconomic class.  However, the use of the term dinner for the midday meal is strongest among working-class people, especially in the English Midlands, North of England and the central belt of Scotland.<ref name=perry/> Even in systems in which dinner is the meal usually eaten at the end of the day, an individual dinner may still refer to a main or more sophisticated meal at any time in the day, such as a [[banquet]], feast, or a special meal eaten on a [[Sunday]] or holiday, such as [[Christmas dinner]] or [[Thanksgiving]] dinner. At such a dinner, the people who dine together may be formally dressed and consume food with an array of [[List of eating utensils|utensils]]. These dinners are often divided into three or more courses. [[Appetizer]]s consisting of options such as soup or salad, precede the [[main course]], which is followed by the [[dessert]].\n\nA survey by [[Orlando Wines#Jacob.27s Creek|Jacob's Creek]], an Australian winemaker, found the average evening meal time in the U.K. to be 7:47pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/average-dinner-time-is-now-747pm-as-work-hours-eat-into-our-meal-times-6648248.html |title=Average dinner time is now 7:47pm as work hours eat into our meal times |newspaper=Evening Standard |date=3 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n\nDave & John (TV Series)\n\nPremiere: Sep 25, 1999\n\nFinale: Dec 16, 2000\n\n\nUPN\n\nSeason One: September 25, 1999 - April 1, 2000 23 Episodes\n\nSeason Two: October 14, 2000 - December 16, 2000 10 Episodes\n\n==Dinner parties==\n{{see also|Party#Dinner party}}\n{{see also|dining in}}\n[[File:Oxford College women in formal dress at dinner n.d. (3193552997).jpg|thumb|[[Oxford Female Institute|Women in formal dress at dinner at Oxford College, Ohio, United States, date unknown]]]]\nA dinner party is a social gathering at which people congregate to eat dinner.<ref name=perry/> Dinners exist on a spectrum, from a basic meal, to a [[state dinner]].<ref name=\"Gazette\" />\n\n===Ancient Rome===\nDuring the times of [[Ancient Rome]], a dinner party was referred to as a ''convivia'', and was a significant event for Roman emperors and senators to congregate and discuss their relations.{{sfn|Edwards|2007|pp=161\u2013162}} The Romans often ate and were also very fond of fish sauce called liquamen (also known as [[Garum]]) during said parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/aug/26/garum-sauce-colatura-di-alici-italy-fish|title=Garum sauce: ancient Rome's 'ketchup' becomes a modern-day secret ingredient|last=Oksman|first=Olga|date=2015-08-26|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nIn London ({{circa|1875}}\u2013{{circa|1900}}), dinner parties were formal occasions that included printed invitations and formal [[RSVP (invitations)|RSVP]]s.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}} The food served at these parties ranged from large, extravagant food displays and several meal [[Course (food)|courses]] to more simple fare and food service.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}} Activities sometimes included singing and poetry reciting, among others.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}}\n\n===Formal dinners===\nA formal dinner has several requirements. First, it requires the participants to wear an [[Evening gown|evening attire]] such as a [[tuxedo]], with either a black or [[white tie]]; second, all food is served from the kitchen; third, \"neither [[:Category:Serving vessels|serving dishes]] nor [[List of serving utensils|utensils]] are placed on the table. All service and table clearing is performed by [[butler]]s and other service staff;\" fourth [[Course (food)|multiple courses]] are served; and finally there is an [[order of service]] and [[seating protocol]]s.<ref name=\"Gazette\">{{cite web |last1=Sennett |first1=Jay |title=Rules of Civility: Dinner Etiquette \u2013 Formal Dining | url = https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/dinner-etiquette-formal-dining/ |website=Gentleman's Gazette |accessdate=2019-08-21 |date=2013-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n\n* [[Early bird dinner]]\n* [[Formal hall]]\n* [[Snack]]\n* [[Supper]]\n* [[Tea (meal)|Tea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book | last=Draznin | first=Y. | title=Victorian London's Middle-class Housewife: What She Did All Day | publisher=Greenwood Press | series=ABC-Clio ebook | year=2001 | isbn=978-0-313-31399-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EdgMLML7DZUC&pg=PA134 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Edwards | first=C. | title=Death in Ancient Rome | publisher=Yale University Press | year=2007 | isbn=978-0-300-11208-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ioq6GmIyLQIC&pg=PA161 | ref = harv}}\n*[[Judith Flanders|Flanders, Judith]], ''The Victorian House: Domestic Life from Childbirth to Deathbed'', 2003, Harper Perennial, {{ISBN|0007131895}} \n* {{cite web \n| first = Sherrie\n| last  = McMillan |year= 2001 |url=http://www.history-magazine.com/dinner2.html |title=What time is dinner? |work=History Magazine |accessdate={{date|23 mar 2015}}}}\n*[[Roy Strong|Strong, Roy]], ''Feast: A History of Grand Eating'', 2002, Jonathan Cape, {{ISBN|0224061380}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n\n* {{cite book | last=Nunn | first=J.J. | title=Mrs. Montague Jones' dinner party: or, Reminiscences of Cheltenham life and manners | publisher=J.C. Hotten | year=1872 | url=https://archive.org/details/mrsmontaguejone00nunngoog}}\n* {{cite book | last=Inness | first=S.A. | title=Dinner Roles: American Women and Culinary Culture | publisher=University of Iowa Press | series=NONE Series | year=2001 | isbn=978-1-58729-332-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzN3bRRIH-gC&printsec=frontcover}}\n* {{cite book | last=Meiselman | first=H.L. | title=Meals in Science and Practice: Interdisciplinary Research and Business Applications | publisher=Elsevier Science | series=Woodhead Publishing Series in Food Science, Technology and Nutrition | year=2009 | isbn=978-1-84569-571-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r8ekAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA97|pages=97\u201398}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nOur (Almost Traditional) Thanksgiving Dinner.jpg|[[Thanksgiving dinner]]\nFile:Christmas table (Serbian cuisine).jpg|[[Christmas dinner]]\nUSDA dinner cropped.jpg|A formal American dinner setting\nFile:Thai Airways airline meal-dinner.JPG|An airline dinner meal\nFile:Asian food.jpg|Japanese dinner \nFile:Jacques Lameloise DSCF6580.jpg|Dinner [[nouvelle cuisine]]   \nFile:Cassoulet mit Gans und Bohnen 1.jpg|[[Cassoulet]] for German dinner\nFile:Tradicinis didkepsnis restorane STEAKHOUSE HAZIENDA.jpg|[[Beef steak]] at a [[steakhouse]] \nFile:STS-129 ISS-21 Crew at the Galley.jpg|A dinner in space aboard the [[ISS]] during [[STS-129]]\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Dinners}}\n* [http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=21847&dict=CALD \"Dinner\" definition] from [[Cambridge University Press|Cambridge.org]]\n* [http://wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookbook Wikibooks Cookbook]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-20243692 BBC article on history of dinner]\n\n{{Meals wide}}\n\n[[Category:Dinner]]\n[[Category:Meals]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{redirect|Dinner time|other uses|Dinner Time (disambiguation){{!}}Dinner Time}}\n{{Meals}}\n'''Dinner''' usually refers to what is in many Western cultures the largest and most formal [[meal]] of the day, which many Westerners eat in the [[evening]].  Historically the largest meal used to be eaten around [[noon|midday]], and called dinner.<ref name=oed>{{cite OED|dinner}}</ref>  In Western cultures, especially among the elite, it gradually migrated later in the day over the 16th to 19th centuries.<ref name=\"mcm\">{{cite web|author1=McMillan S|title=What Time is Dinner?|url=http://www.history-magazine.com/dinner2.html|publisher=History Magazine|accessdate=31 December 2017|date=2001}}</ref>  However, the word \"dinner\" can have different meanings depending on culture, and may mean a meal of any size eaten at any time of day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olver|first=Lynne|title=Meal times|url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodfaq7.html#mealtimes|publisher=Lynne Olver|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>  In particular it is still sometimes used for a meal at noon or in the early afternoon on special occasions, such as a [[Christmas dinner]].<ref name=mcm/>  In very hot climates people have always tended to eat the main meal in the evening, after the temperature has fallen.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Family eating meal.jpg|thumb|Dinner with family]]\nThe word is from the Old French ({{circa|1300}}) ''disner'', meaning \"dine\", from the stem of Gallo-Romance ''desjunare'' (\"to break one's fast\"), from Latin ''dis-'' (which indicates the opposite of an action) + Late Latin ''ieiunare'' (\"to fast\"), from Latin ''ieiunus'' (\"fasting, hungry\").<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=dinner Etymology of \"dinner\"] from Online Dictionary. Accessed November 11, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=dine Etymology of \"dine\"] from Online Dictionary. Accessed November 11, 2009.</ref> The [[Romanian language|Romanian]] word ''dejun'' and the [[French language|French]] ''d\u00e9jeuner'' retain this etymology and to some extent the meaning (whereas the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word ''desayuno'' and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] ''desjejum'' are related but are exclusively used for breakfast). Eventually, the term shifted to referring to the heavy main meal of the day, even if it had been preceded by a breakfast meal (or even both breakfast and lunch).\n\n==Time of day==\n===Historical===\nReflecting the typical custom of the 17th century, [[Louis XIV]] dined at noon, with a [[supper]] at 10pm.<ref>Strong, 250</ref>   But in [[Europe]], dinner began to move later in the day during the 1700s, due to developments in work practices, lighting, financial status, and cultural changes.<ref name=mcm/>  The fashionable hour for dinner continued to be incrementally postponed during the 18th century, to two and three in the afternoon, and in 1765 King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] dined at 4pm, though his infant sons had theirs with their governess at 2pm, leaving time to visit the queen as she dressed for dinner with the king.<ref>\"Text adapted from ''The Conversation Piece: Scenes of fashionable life'', London, 2009\", at  [http://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/search#/1/collection/400146/queen-charlotte-1744-1818-with-her-two-eldest-sons \"Johan Joseph Zoffany (Frankfurt 1733-London 1810), Queen Charlotte (1744\u20131818) with her Two Eldest Sons  c.1765\"] on the Royal Collection website.</ref>  But in France [[Marie Antoinette]], when still [[Dauphine of France]] in 1770, wrote that when at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Choisy]] the court still dined at 2pm, with a supper after the theatre at around 10pm, before bed at 1 or 1.30am.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=A7E-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA110 quoted in] ''The Origins of Contemporary France: The ancient r\u00e9gime'', by [[Hippolyte Taine]], Bk2, ch.1, p. 110 in this edition</ref>\n\nAt the time of the [[First French Empire]] an English traveler to [[Paris]] remarked upon the \"abominable habit of dining as late as seven in the evening\".<ref>Quote in Ian Kelly, ''Cooking for Kings: the life of Antonin Car\u00eame the first celebrity chef'', 2003:78. For guests of [[Talleyrand]] at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Valen\u00e7ay]], dinner under [[Antonin Car\u00eame|Car\u00eame]] was even later.</ref>  By about 1850 English middle-class dinners were around 5 or 6pm, allowing men to arrive back from work, but there was a continuing pressure for the hour to drift later, led by the elite who did not have to work set hours, and as commutes got longer as cities expanded.  In the mid-19th century the issue was something of a social minefield, with a generational element.  [[John Ruskin]], once he married in 1848, dined at 6pm, which his parents thought \"unhealthy\".  [[Mrs Gaskell]] dined between 4 and 5pm.  The fictional [[The Diary of a Nobody|Mr Pooter]], a lower middle-class Londoner in 1888-89 and a diner at 5pm, was invited by his son to dine at 8pm, but \"I said we did not pretend to be fashionable people, and would like the dinner earlier\".<ref>Flanders, 229-230</ref>\n\nThe satirical novel ''Living for Appearances'' (1855) by [[Henry Mayhew]] and his brother [[Augustus Mayhew|Augustus]] begins with the views of the hero on the matter.  He dines at 7pm, and often complains of \"the disgusting and tradesman-like custom of early dining\", say at 2pm.  The \"Royal hour\" he regards as 8pm, but he does not aspire to that.  He tells people \"Tell me when you dine, and I will tell you what you are\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aq4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1 ''Living for Appearances''] (1855), p. 1, by [[Henry Mayhew]] and his brother [[Augustus Mayhew|Augustus]]; Flanders, 230</ref>\n\n===Modern===\n[[File:Filet de b\u0153uf.jpg|thumb|A [[filet mignon]] dinner with mashed potato, string beans and mushrooms.]]\nIn many modern usages, the term ''dinner'' refers to the evening meal, which is now typically the largest meal of the day in Western cultures. When this meaning is used, the preceding meals are usually referred to as [[breakfast]], [[lunch]] and perhaps a [[Tea (meal)|tea]].<ref name=mcm/><ref name=\"perry\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/aug/03/tea-with-grayson-perry-supper-dinner |title=Tea with Grayson Perry. Or is it dinner, or supper? |newspaper=The Guardian |date=August 2012 |accessdate=2013-08-15 |location=London}}</ref>  [[Supper]] is now often an alternative term for dinner; originally this was always a later secondary evening meal, after an early dinner.\n\nThe divide between different meanings of \"dinner\" is not cut-and-dried based on either geography or socioeconomic class.  However, the use of the term dinner for the midday meal is strongest among working-class people, especially in the English Midlands, North of England and the central belt of Scotland.<ref name=perry/> Even in systems in which dinner is the meal usually eaten at the end of the day, an individual dinner may still refer to a main or more sophisticated meal at any time in the day, such as a [[banquet]], feast, or a special meal eaten on a [[Sunday]] or holiday, such as [[Christmas dinner]] or [[Thanksgiving]] dinner. At such a dinner, the people who dine together may be formally dressed and consume food with an array of [[List of eating utensils|utensils]]. These dinners are often divided into three or more courses. [[Appetizer]]s consisting of options such as soup or salad, precede the [[main course]], which is followed by the [[dessert]].\n\nA survey by [[Orlando Wines#Jacob.27s Creek|Jacob's Creek]], an Australian winemaker, found the average evening meal time in the U.K. to be 7:47pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/average-dinner-time-is-now-747pm-as-work-hours-eat-into-our-meal-times-6648248.html |title=Average dinner time is now 7:47pm as work hours eat into our meal times |newspaper=Evening Standard |date=3 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Dinner parties==\n{{see also|Party#Dinner party}}\n{{see also|dining in}}\n[[File:Oxford College women in formal dress at dinner n.d. (3193552997).jpg|thumb|[[Oxford Female Institute|Women in formal dress at dinner at Oxford College, Ohio, United States, date unknown]]]]\nA dinner party is a social gathering at which people congregate to eat dinner.<ref name=perry/> Dinners exist on a spectrum, from a basic meal, to a [[state dinner]].<ref name=\"Gazette\" />\n\n===Ancient Rome===\nDuring the times of [[Ancient Rome]], a dinner party was referred to as a ''convivia'', and was a significant event for Roman emperors and senators to congregate and discuss their relations.{{sfn|Edwards|2007|pp=161\u2013162}} The Romans often ate and were also very fond of fish sauce called liquamen (also known as [[Garum]]) during said parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/aug/26/garum-sauce-colatura-di-alici-italy-fish|title=Garum sauce: ancient Rome's 'ketchup' becomes a modern-day secret ingredient|last=Oksman|first=Olga|date=2015-08-26|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nIn London ({{circa|1875}}\u2013{{circa|1900}}), dinner parties were formal occasions that included printed invitations and formal [[RSVP (invitations)|RSVP]]s.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}} The food served at these parties ranged from large, extravagant food displays and several meal [[Course (food)|courses]] to more simple fare and food service.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}} Activities sometimes included singing and poetry reciting, among others.{{sfn|Draznin|2001|pp=134-136}}\n\n===Formal dinners===\nA formal dinner has several requirements. First, it requires the participants to wear an [[Evening gown|evening attire]] such as a [[tuxedo]], with either a black or [[white tie]]; second, all food is served from the kitchen; third, \"neither [[:Category:Serving vessels|serving dishes]] nor [[List of serving utensils|utensils]] are placed on the table. All service and table clearing is performed by [[butler]]s and other service staff;\" fourth [[Course (food)|multiple courses]] are served; and finally there is an [[order of service]] and [[seating protocol]]s.<ref name=\"Gazette\">{{cite web |last1=Sennett |first1=Jay |title=Rules of Civility: Dinner Etiquette \u2013 Formal Dining | url = https://www.gentlemansgazette.com/dinner-etiquette-formal-dining/ |website=Gentleman's Gazette |accessdate=2019-08-21 |date=2013-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n\n* [[Early bird dinner]]\n* [[Formal hall]]\n* [[Snack]]\n* [[Supper]]\n* [[Tea (meal)|Tea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book | last=Draznin | first=Y. | title=Victorian London's Middle-class Housewife: What She Did All Day | publisher=Greenwood Press | series=ABC-Clio ebook | year=2001 | isbn=978-0-313-31399-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EdgMLML7DZUC&pg=PA134 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Edwards | first=C. | title=Death in Ancient Rome | publisher=Yale University Press | year=2007 | isbn=978-0-300-11208-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ioq6GmIyLQIC&pg=PA161 | ref = harv}}\n*[[Judith Flanders|Flanders, Judith]], ''The Victorian House: Domestic Life from Childbirth to Deathbed'', 2003, Harper Perennial, {{ISBN|0007131895}} \n* {{cite web \n| first = Sherrie\n| last  = McMillan |year= 2001 |url=http://www.history-magazine.com/dinner2.html |title=What time is dinner? |work=History Magazine |accessdate={{date|23 mar 2015}}}}\n*[[Roy Strong|Strong, Roy]], ''Feast: A History of Grand Eating'', 2002, Jonathan Cape, {{ISBN|0224061380}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin|2}}\n\n* {{cite book | last=Nunn | first=J.J. | title=Mrs. Montague Jones' dinner party: or, Reminiscences of Cheltenham life and manners | publisher=J.C. Hotten | year=1872 | url=https://archive.org/details/mrsmontaguejone00nunngoog}}\n* {{cite book | last=Inness | first=S.A. | title=Dinner Roles: American Women and Culinary Culture | publisher=University of Iowa Press | series=NONE Series | year=2001 | isbn=978-1-58729-332-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzN3bRRIH-gC&printsec=frontcover}}\n* {{cite book | last=Meiselman | first=H.L. | title=Meals in Science and Practice: Interdisciplinary Research and Business Applications | publisher=Elsevier Science | series=Woodhead Publishing Series in Food Science, Technology and Nutrition | year=2009 | isbn=978-1-84569-571-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r8ekAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA97|pages=97\u201398}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nOur (Almost Traditional) Thanksgiving Dinner.jpg|[[Thanksgiving dinner]]\nFile:Christmas table (Serbian cuisine).jpg|[[Christmas dinner]]\nUSDA dinner cropped.jpg|A formal American dinner setting\nFile:Thai Airways airline meal-dinner.JPG|An airline dinner meal\nFile:Asian food.jpg|Japanese dinner \nFile:Jacques Lameloise DSCF6580.jpg|Dinner [[nouvelle cuisine]]   \nFile:Cassoulet mit Gans und Bohnen 1.jpg|[[Cassoulet]] for German dinner\nFile:Tradicinis didkepsnis restorane STEAKHOUSE HAZIENDA.jpg|[[Beef steak]] at a [[steakhouse]] \nFile:STS-129 ISS-21 Crew at the Galley.jpg|A dinner in space aboard the [[ISS]] during [[STS-129]]\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Dinners}}\n* [http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=21847&dict=CALD \"Dinner\" definition] from [[Cambridge University Press|Cambridge.org]]\n* [http://wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookbook Wikibooks Cookbook]\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-20243692 BBC article on history of dinner]\n\n{{Meals wide}}\n\n[[Category:Dinner]]\n[[Category:Meals]]\n", "name_user": "Kaseyk2019", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Little Bit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinner"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wyoming", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Wyoming, United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wyoming\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 in Wyoming.svg\n| legend1         = {{Center|Map of counties in Wyoming with confirmed cases (as of April 10):}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#ffffff|No confirmed cases reported}}\n{{legend|#fee5d9|<5 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fcbba1|5-10 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|11-20 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fb6a4a|21-50 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|51-100 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#a50f15|>100 confirmed cases}}|left = 3}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Wyoming]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Sheridan County, Wyoming|Sheridan County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| origin          = [[California]], U.S.\n| confirmed_cases = 322<ref name=\"WDPHE-official\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=42fd398fa8f449fb930f2d3755c5a1bb |website=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = 119<ref name=\"WDPHE-official\"/>\n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 254<ref name=\"WDPHE-official\"/>\n| deaths          = 6<ref name=\"WDPHE-official\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.wyo.gov/}}\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Wyoming]] in March 2020. On April 13, Wyoming became the last state in the U.S. to report its first death from COVID-19.<ref><https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/infectious-disease-epidemiology-unit/disease/novel-coronavirus/covid-19-map-and-statistics/></ref> On April 14th, Wyoming reported its 2nd COVID-19 related death.<ref><https://www.wyomingnewsnow.tv/content/news/2nd-Covid-19-related-death-in-Wyoming-confirmed-569660141.html></ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Wyoming medical cases chart}}\n* March 11, 2020: First reported case of [[COVID-19]] is a woman in [[Sheridan County, Wyoming|Sheridan County]] who recently travelled domestically.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-wyoming/article_0b075aea-a3ab-58d8-b5bd-a5b03b764075.html|title=First coronavirus case reported in Wyoming|date=11 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-date=March 18, 2020|work=[[Casper Star-Tribune]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200318223119/https://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-wyoming/article_0b075aea-a3ab-58d8-b5bd-a5b03b764075.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-19/coronavirus-wyoming-covid-19-casper-idaho|title=Think the most isolated corners of the U.S. are safe from coronavirus? Think again|first=Maria L.|last=La Ganga|newspaper=[[LA Times]]|date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13, 2020: Second reported case is a man in Fremont County.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/second-wyoming-case-of-coronavirus-identified/article_1945cbeb-a94d-542d-b08c-26c3fa58dc2f.html|title=Second Wyoming case of coronavirus identified|date=13 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200318222952/https://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/second-wyoming-case-of-coronavirus-identified/article_1945cbeb-a94d-542d-b08c-26c3fa58dc2f.html|work=Casper Star-Tribune|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 15, 2020: Governor Gordon recommends closing all public schools.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oilcity.news/community/health/covid-19/2020/03/15/natrona-county-school-district-closing-schools-starting-monday-amid-covid-19-pandemic/|title=Natrona County School District Closind Schools Starting Monday Amid COVID-19 Pandemic|date=15 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-date=March 16, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200316131645/https://oilcity.news/community/health/covid-19/2020/03/15/natrona-county-school-district-closing-schools-starting-monday-amid-covid-19-pandemic/|work=Oil City News|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 18, 2020: Third positive case in [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]], brings the state count up to 16 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trib.com/news/local/casper/third-person-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-in-cheyenne-bringing-state/article_2b32b003-f677-512e-9286-e8c4de4988c3.html|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020|title=Third person tests positive for coronavirus in Cheyenne, bringing state total to 16|work=Casper Star-Tribune|archive-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200318223539/https://trib.com/news/local/casper/third-person-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-in-cheyenne-bringing-state/article_2b32b003-f677-512e-9286-e8c4de4988c3.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Responses==\nOn March 17, Wyoming Governor [[Mark Gordon (politician)|Mark Gordon]] \"announced the creation of five task forces designed to tackle the effects of the spreading coronavirus\", and condemned [[Hoarding (economics)|hoarding]] in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trib.com/news/state-and-regional/health/wyoming-governor-announces-creation-of-five-task-forces-to-battle/article_428b9637-01b9-5533-ba53-af7a14542ce2.html|title=Wyoming governor announces creation of five task forces to battle effects of coronavirus|first1=Seth|last1=Klamann|first2=Morgan|last2=Hughes|publisher=[[Casper Star-Tribune]]|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndustries have had varying responses, with energy companies in the state trying to balance safety with continued productivity by imposing quarantine and travel restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trib.com/business/energy/energy-companies-in-wyoming-intensify-response-to-coronavirus-outbreak/article_6fd14076-9f24-5655-8967-60ef7488b590.html|title=Energy companies in Wyoming intensify response to coronavirus outbreak|first=Camille|last=Erickson|publisher=Casper Star-Tribune|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=\"ncaa\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships |last=Osburn |first=Stacey |date=March 12, 2020 |website=NCAA |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{Cite news |last=DeCamp |first=Scott |url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |title=NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak |date=2020-03-16 |work=MLive.com |access-date=2020-03-25 |language=en}}</ref> High school sports were also cancelled.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Wyoming\nUpdated April 21, 2020<